mV3cy1yZWxlYXNlcy9mdHgtbGF1bmNoZXMtc3RyYXRlZ2ljLXJldmlldy1vZi1pdHMtZ2xvYmFs=
LWFzc2V0cy0zMDE2ODMyNjkuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6466cd13" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 FTX announced</a> that it was =E2=80=9Claunching a strategic review of the=
ir global assets to begin to maximize recoverable value for stakeholders,=
=E2=80=9D engaging Perella Weinberg Partners LP to try to sell =E2=80=9Cman=
y regulated or licensed subsidiaries of FTX,=E2=80=9D the ones that=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Chave solvent balance sheets, responsible management and valuable f=
ranchises.=E2=80=9D If you run a big sprawling crypto trading enterprise, a=
nd your main enterprise loses a ton of money on bad trades and finds itself=
 insolvent, then there might be lots of other barely-related businesses tha=
t are perfectly solvent and keep operating normally, and you can sell them =
off to raise money to pay off creditors of the main business. If on the oth=
er hand the main enterprise=C2=A0<em>steals=C2=A0</em>a bunch of customer m=
oney, that sort of makes everyone else look bad? Harder to find buyers, in =
that case. I suppose the argument is that the more=C2=A0<em>regulated=C2=A0=
</em>subsidiaries were not in on any wrongdoing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere, =E2=80=9CPeople Are Already Buying =
Depositor Claims on FTX,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/29765114.257546/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMTcvcGVvcGxlLWFyZS1hbHJlYWR5LWJ1eWluZy1kZXBvc2l0b3ItY2=
